                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12588413" author="karl.wettin" created="Sun, 13 Apr 2008 20:02:22 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Requires DistanceMeasure#distance(Vector, Vector):double&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12588414" author="jeastman@windwardsolutions.com" created="Sun, 13 Apr 2008 20:03:30 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;This should be straightforward, as DistanceMeasure extends JobConfigurable.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12588416" author="karl.wettin" created="Sun, 13 Apr 2008 20:10:33 +0100"  >&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;WeightedDistanceMeasure&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;WeightedManhattanDistanceMeasure&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;WeightedEuclideanDistanceMeasure&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;It&apos;s very possible I&apos;ve got the weights in the wrong place. Can someone please check that?&lt;/p&gt;

</comment>
                            <comment id="12588606" author="jeastman@windwardsolutions.com" created="Mon, 14 Apr 2008 16:11:39 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The problem  I see with including the weights in the JobConf is that it requires the user to edit the program to change the weights. Perhaps that is what you meant by &apos;too static&apos;? I&apos;d suggest breaking out the string literal into a proper constant e.g. &apos;org.apache.mahout.utility.distancemeasure.weights&apos; or somesuch. Putting the weights in a file and making the JobConf argument be the file name would make changing them easier. ClusterMapper has such an implementation.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12588707" author="karl.wettin" created="Mon, 14 Apr 2008 19:47:16 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll fix it as a file.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m still new to handling Hadoop &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12589817" author="karl.wettin" created="Thu, 17 Apr 2008 04:10:42 +0100"  >&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;AbstractDistanceMeasure - shows why abstract classes is prefered to interfaces for backwards compatibillity&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;WeightedDistanceMeasure - now loads a sparse vector from a file&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;WeightedEuclideanMeasure - did I get the weights in the right place?&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;WeightedManhattanMeasure - did I get the weights in the right place?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;DefaultDistanceMeasureTest - assert a few standard measurements behaviours&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;DefaultWeightedDistanceMeasureTest - assert a few standard weight behaviours&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;factory implementations (hi Grant!) for all distance measure classes&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12590168" author="karl.wettin" created="Thu, 17 Apr 2008 20:22:51 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll commit this tomorrow If nobody objects to how I add weights in WeightedEuclideanMeasure and WeightedManhattanMeasure.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12590186" author="samee.zahur" created="Thu, 17 Apr 2008 20:56:11 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Just a suggestion:&lt;br/&gt;
Could we not give the programmers the choice of whether or not they want to load weights? I was thinking if we could give WeightedDistanceMeasure overloaded constructors (Default one without params, that wouldn&apos;t load a weight, the other with a file path that would) so that programmers can easily choose whether or not to load weights and if so then from where.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12590589" author="karl.wettin" created="Fri, 18 Apr 2008 20:40:37 +0100"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Could we not give the programmers the choice of whether or not they want to load weights?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If weights is not set in configure or with the setter method these methods will fall back on non weighted calculation. These classes are so small and simple I don&apos;t mind a duplicate set. The only thing is that they don&apos;t share the same code, it is cloned. I&apos;ll fix that before I commit.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12590591" author="karl.wettin" created="Fri, 18 Apr 2008 20:42:36 +0100"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll fix that before I commit.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;10 seconds later I changed my mind. I&apos;ll just commit.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12590596" author="karl.wettin" created="Fri, 18 Apr 2008 21:05:49 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;committed&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
